    Introduction

    In this Lab Step, you'll learn how to update and edit a manifest file to create a new Deployment resource within the cluster. Deployments represent a set of multiple, identical Pods and have the ability to automatically replace failing or unresponsive instances. In this scenario a Deployment will be used to launch a single pod containing two containers. The first container is a NGINX web server container which proxies incoming HTTP requests downstream to a second container running a FLASK based web application - which you created in the first Lab Step. 

    Instructions  

    1. Within the Explorer view, navigate to and open the lab/code/App/lab-code/k8s/deployment.yaml manifest file.

    Take sometime to review and understand the design and intent of the deployment.yaml manifest file:

    2. Add the NGINX container configuration.

    Edit and update the deployment.yaml manifest file by adding the following directly beneath the #Code2.0 comment block:

    #CODE2.0:
    #add the NGINX container to the pod - configure it to mount the nginx.conf file stored in the nginx-conf configMap 
    - name: nginx
      image: nginx:1.13.7
      imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent
      ports:
      - name: http
        containerPort: 80
      volumeMounts:
      - name: nginx-proxy-config
        mountPath: /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf
        subPath: nginx.conf

    This provides the NGINX web server container configuration. Notice how it mounts the NGINX config stored in the respective ConfigMap resource you created in the previous Lab Step.

    3. Add the FLASKAPP container configuration. 

    Note: The container image tag name cloudacademydevops/flask referenced here is intentionally wrong. You will learn how to troubleshoot and fix this in the following steps.

    Edit and update the deployment.yaml manifest file by adding the following directly beneath the #Code2.1 comment block:

    #CODE2.1:
    #add the FLASK container to the pod
    - name: flask
      image: cloudacademydevops/flask
      imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent
      ports:
      - name: http
        containerPort: 5000
      env:
      - name: APP_NAME
        value: CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest

    This provides the FLASKAPP web server container configuration. Notice how it uses an environment variable named APP_NAME to store a string that will be used in the HTTP response at runtime - this container is based on the custom Docker image you created in the first Lab Step.

    4. Edit and update the deployment.yaml manifest file by adding the following directly beneath the #Code2.2 comment block:

    #CODE2.2:
    #reference the nginx-conf configMap - this will be mounted into the NGINX container
    - name: nginx-proxy-config
      configMap:
        name: nginx-conf

    This references the ConfigMap containing the NGINX web server configuration created in the previous Lab Step

    Notes:

    • The image name for the FLASK container cloudacademydevops/flask is intentionally wrong - you will learn to troubleshoot and fix this in the remaining steps
    • Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated deployment.yaml file BEFORE proceeding onto the next step - this is very important!!
    • Make sure that the indentation is maintained
    • Consider copying the content directly from the provided version found in the equivalent solution-code directory: lab/code/App/solution-code/k8s/deployment.yaml

    The updated file deployment.yaml manifest file should now look like the following:

    5. Apply the updated deployment.yaml file into the K8s cluster - this will create a new Deployment resource. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

    6. List out all of the deployments in the K8s cluster. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get deploy 

    Notice how the frontend deployment is showing 0/1 replicas READY. Let's now troubleshoot and fix this.

    7. List out all of the pods in the K8s cluster. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get pods

    Notice how the frontend pod has 1/2 containers in a READY state, and that there is an ErrImagePull issue. Let's now troubleshoot and fix this.

    8. Extract the frontend pod name and store it in a variable named POD_NAME. Echo it back out to the terminal. In the terminal execute the following commands:

    POD_NAME=`kubectl get pods -o jsonpath='{.items[0].metadata.name}'`
    echo $POD_NAME

    9. Now use the kubectl describe command to get a detailed report on the current status of the frontend pod. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl describe pod $POD_NAME


    Take sometime to review the Events section of the previous output. You can clearly observe that there was an issue trying to pull down the non-existent cloudacademydevops/flask docker image. This was due to the intentional mistake introduced in step 3 above. 

    10. Use the docker images command to confirm the correct docker image tag for the FLASK based web application that you built in Lab Step 1. In the terminal execute the following command:

    docker images | grep cloudacademydevops

    Here you can see that indeed the correct image tag is cloudacademydevops/flaskapp.

    11. Now use the sed command to perform an inline find for the incorrect image tag cloudacademydevops/flask and replace it with the correct image tag cloudacademydevops/flaskapp within the deployment.yaml file. In the terminal execute the following command:

    sed -i 's/cloudacademydevops\/flask/cloudacademydevops\/flaskapp/g' deployment.yaml

    12. Within the Editor view, confirm that the updated file deployment.yaml manifest file is now using the correct container image tag for the FLASK container (line 35):

    13. Apply the updated deployment.yaml file back into the K8s cluster - this will update the existing Deployment resource. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

    14. List out all of the Deployment resourses in the K8s cluster. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get deploy 

    Notice how the frontend deployment is now showing 1/1 replicas READY. This confirms that we have corrected and fixed the previous mistake!!

    15. Expose the frontend deployment. This will create a new Service resource which will allow the frontend pods to be called via a stable cluster network VIP address . In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl expose deployment frontend --port=80 --target-port=80

    16. List out the new frontend Service resource previously created. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get svc frontend 

    17. Extract the frontend service cluster IP address and store it in a variable named FRONTEND_SERVICE_IP. Echo it back out to the terminal. In the terminal execute the following commands:

    FRONTEND_SERVICE_IP=`kubectl get service/frontend -o jsonpath='{.spec.clusterIP}'`
    echo $FRONTEND_SERVICE_IP

    18. Test the frontend service by sending a curl request to it. In the terminal execute the following command:

    curl -i http://$FRONTEND_SERVICE_IP

    Confirm that the body of the HTTP response contains the string "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest". This demonstrates how to leverage environment variables at runtime. Recall that the APP_NAME environment variable as declared within the deployment.yaml manifest file specified the value "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest". The resulting string is then used at runtime within the FLASK web application container, and is returned within the body of the HTTP response when requested - as just observed.

    19. Edit and update the deployment.yaml manifest file by updating the APP_NAME environment variable to be "CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest.v2.00", like so:

    Note: Make sure that you save (CTRL+S) the updated deployment.yaml file again BEFORE proceeding onto the next step! 

    20. Apply the updated deployment.yaml file back into the K8s cluster - this will update the existing frontend Deployment resource. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

    21. Retest the frontend service by sending a new curl request to it. In the terminal execute the following command:

    curl -i http://$FRONTEND_SERVICE_IP

    Confirm that the body of the HTTP response contains the UPDATED string "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest.v2.00". 

    22. Let's now examine the logs associated with sending traffic through the NGINX web server. For starters list out the current pods within the cluster. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl get pods 

    Note: Repeat the above command until the output only shows the single RUNNING pod before moving onto the next instruction.

    23. Extract the frontend pod name and store it in a variable named FRONTEND_POD_NAME. Echo it back out to the terminal. In the terminal execute the following commands:

    FRONTEND_POD_NAME=`kubectl get pods --no-headers -o custom-columns=":metadata.name"`
    echo $FRONTEND_POD_NAME

    24. Perform a directory listing directly within the NGINX container listing out the contents of the /var/log/nginx directory. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl exec -it $FRONTEND_POD_NAME -c nginx -- ls -la /var/log/nginx/

    Notice how both the access.log and error.log files are pointers to /dev/stdout and /dev/stderr. This implies that the NGINX traffic logging statements will be passed out to and available via the kubectl logs command - let's try this out.

    25. Use the kubectl logs command to examine the NGINX logging generated by the previously executed curl commands . In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl logs $FRONTEND_POD_NAME nginx

    26. Use the kubectl logs command to examine the FLASK logging generated by the previously executed curl commands. In the terminal execute the following command:

    kubectl logs $FRONTEND_POD_NAME flask

     

       

    Summary

    In this Lab Step, you updated, saved, and applied the deployment.yaml manifest file into the K8s cluster. This created a new Deployment which contained a NGINX web server container configured to proxy incoming HTTP requests downstream to a second container running a FLASK based web application. In the next Lab Step we'll introduce you to Helm which can be used to templatetize manifest files making them more reusable.

    Validation checks
    2Checks
    Check Deployment Exists

    Check the frontend deployment now exists with 1 running replica

    Check the Correct Web Response is Returned

    Check that the body of the HTTP response contains the substring "Hello World - CloudAcademy.DevOps.K8s.Manifest"
